04300nam a22006015i 9780226188379DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016033493  a9780226188379  a(DE-B1597)550284  a(OCoLC)980875215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDS109.925b.L4613 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh  aNR 9035qDE-24/20sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/130228:1 aLemire, Vincent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJerusalem 1900 :bThe Holy City in the Age of Possibilities /cVincent Lemire. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b22 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tTranslators’ Note -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Underside of Maps -- t2. Origins of the City as Museum -- t3. Still-Undetermined Holy Sites -- t4. The Scale of the Empire -- t5. The Municipal Revolution -- t6. The Wild Revolutionary Days of 1908 -- t7. Intersecting Identities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerhaps the most contested patch of earth in the world, Jerusalem’s Old City experiences consistent violent unrest between Israeli and Palestinian residents, with seemingly no end in sight. Today, Jerusalem’s endless cycle of riots and arrests appears intractable—even unavoidable—and it looks unlikely that harmony will ever be achieved in the city. But with Jerusalem 1900, historian Vincent Lemire shows us that it wasn’t always that way, undoing the familiar notion of Jerusalem as a lost cause and revealing a unique moment in history when a more peaceful future seemed possible. In this masterly history, Lemire uses newly opened archives to explore how Jerusalem’s elite residents of differing faiths cooperated through an intercommunity municipal council they created in the mid-1860s to administer the affairs of all inhabitants and improve their shared city. These residents embraced a spirit of modern urbanism and cultivated a civic identity that transcended religion and reflected the relatively secular and cosmopolitan way of life of Jerusalem at the time. These few years would turn out to be a tipping point in the city’s history—a pivotal moment when the horizon of possibility was still open, before the council broke up in 1934, under British rule, into separate Jewish and Arab factions. Uncovering this often overlooked diplomatic period, Lemire reveals that the struggle over Jerusalem was not historically inevitable—and therefore is not necessarily intractable. Jerusalem 1900 sheds light on how the Holy City once functioned peacefully and illustrates how it might one day do so again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMunicipal governmentzJerusalem. 0aUrban anthropologyzJerusalem. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  a19th Century.  aEretz Israel.  aJerusalem.  aMiddle East.  aOttoman Empire.  aPalestine.  aUrbanity.1 aTihanyi, Catherine.1 aWeiss, Lys Ann.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226188379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226188379/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles